The alloy exhibits mainly a uniform near lamellar (NL) structure with a colony size of about 70μm. No dendritic core can be seen, and the colony size of the rim and center of the ingot is the same. Fig. 2
 shows SEM images using backscattered electrons showing the lamellar colonies and γ grains and retained β phase at colony boundaries and triple junctions. The volume fraction of the β phase is about 8%. Average lamellar spacing measured by TEM is about 700nm (Fig. 3
). Higher magnification images such as Fig. 4
 indicate that some of the β phases exist in the lamellar colony either in the lamellar morphology paralleling to α2/γ lamella, or in the patchy morphology interrupting the continuity of the α2/γ lamella. It should be noted that there is a random distribution of the borides showing bright contrast in SEM-BSE images of the microstructure. The composition of the borides measured by EDS is shown in Table 1
. The boride phases in the alloy appear in three distinct morphologies: convoluted flakes, ribbons and particles (Fig. 5
). Some bright particles containing mainly of the Y and O are also seen. It is Y2O3 as confirmed by others [6]. The only way to differentiate between boride particles and Y2O3 particles is to examine their compositions by EDS due to their similar appearance and contrast.
